# Three-lens review vs external documentation

When doing delivery write-ups, the **three-lens review** means the mandatory passes: **devil’s advocate**, **expert technical writer**, and **senior staff engineer** (as in FUNK-what-we-did).

**Do not** put three-lens blocks, role-play narration (“as devil’s advocate…”), or internal retro voice into **user-facing** docs.

**User-facing** includes at least: `README.md`, `docs/**`, top-level guides, `pyproject.toml` `description` / README-driven metadata, and similar material a newcomer or downstream user reads to use the project.

**Appropriate places** for three-lens content: PR descriptions (optional section), chat handoffs, internal notes, `docs/delivery/` or team-agreed paths, and agent session output—not the main README unless the project explicitly documents its own review process for external readers.

When editing external docs, keep prose **direct** (what it does, how to run it, limitations). Fold review conclusions into **short, factual** statements (e.g. “Requires `uv` on PATH”) without framing them as a lens or review transcript.
